{"key":"post-14039449","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>14039449</id>\n<content>It's all about strain isolation.&amp;nbsp; A rock on a petri dish indicates a sclerotia producing strain, just as a fruit growing on a petri dish indicates a fruiting strain.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I also don't recommend against cloning.&amp;nbsp; The oyster strain I grow commercially, I cloned from the wild back in 2004 and am still using that exact culture after growing tens of thousands of pounds of mushrooms from it.&amp;nbsp; What I recommend against is cloning from a later flush or cloning the largest fruit.&amp;nbsp; In addition, a clone may or may not be an isolate.&amp;nbsp; If it sectors, fruit each sector to determine the best one.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't confuse advice to save culture slants over cloning as saying cloning is bad.&amp;nbsp; It's just that if you refrigerate and save a slant before you fruit the culture, you have saved younger cell lines which will perform better in the future.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>14039398</prev>\n<first>14024492</first>\n<last>14039449</last>\n<when>1298872077</when>\n<utime>02/28/11 07:47 AM</utime>\n</post>"}